{"cursor":"2737","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Pearson symbol', or 'Pearson notation', is used in crystallography as a\nmeans of describing a crystal structure, and was originated by W.B.\nPearson. W.B. Pearson, A Handbook of Lattice Spacings and Structures of\nMetals and Alloys,Vol. 2, Pergamon Press, Oxford, 1967 The symbol is made\nup of two letters followed by a number. For example:\n* Diamond structure, cF8\n* Rutile structure, tP6\n\nThe two (italicised) letters specify the Bravais lattice. The lower case letter\nspecifies the crystal class, and the upper case letter the lattice type. The\nfigure gives the number of the atoms in the unit cell. IUPAC (2005)\n[http://old.iupac.org/publications/books/rbook/Red_Book_2005.pdf\nNomenclature of Inorganic Chemistry IUPAC Recommendations 2005]; IR-3.4.4, pp.49-\n51; IR-11.5, pp.241-242\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Crystal class a|| triclinic - m|| monoclinic - o|| orthorhombic - t||\n|  tetragonal - h || hexagonal and rhombohedral - c || cubic }\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Lattice type S,A,B,C ||Side face centred - F||All face centred - I||Body\n|  centred (from 'i'nnenzentrierte ) page 124 in\n|  chapter 3. Crystallography: Internal order and symmetry in Cornelius Klein &\n|  Cornelius S. Hurlbut, Jr.: Manual of Mineralogy, 21st edition, 1993, John\n|  Wiley & Sons, Inc., ISBN 0-471-59955-7 - R||Rhombohedral -\n|  P||Primitive }\nThe letters A, B and C was formerly used instead of S. When centering had a pair\nof opposite faces along the X-axis it was called A-centered. Equivalent\ncentering along the Y- and Z-axes were called B- and C-centered, respective.\n\nThe fourteen possible Bravais lattices are identified by the first two letters:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Crystal class!!Lattice symbol!!Pearson symbol letters\n|-\n|Triclinic||P||aP\n|-\n|Monoclinic || P ||mP\n|-\n| ||S ||mS\n|-\n|Orthorhombic ||P||oP\n|-\n| || S||oS\n|-\n| ||F||oF\n|-\n| ||I||oI\n|-\n|Tetragonal|| P||tP\n|-\n| ||I||tI\n|-\n|Hexagonal (and trigonal)|| P||hP\n|-\n|Rhombohedral|| R||hR\n|-\n|Cubic||P||cP\n|-\n| ||F||cF\n|-\n| ||I||cI\n|}\n","linknr":96,"url":"Pearson_symbol","recorded":1371246007,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Crystallography","/wiki/Crystal_structure","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Bravais_lattice","/wiki/IUPAC_nomenclature_of_inorganic_chemistry_2005","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-Klein_.26_Hurlbut-3","#cite_note-Klein_.26_Hurlbut-3","/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Space_group","/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&action=edit&section=2","#cite_ref-1","#cite_ref-2","http://old.iupac.org/publications/books/rbook/Red_Book_2005.pdf","#cite_ref-Klein_.26_Hurlbut_3-0","#cite_ref-Klein_.26_Hurlbut_3-1","/wiki/Special:BookSources/0471599557","/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&action=edit&section=3","http://cst-www.nrl.navy.mil/lattice/pearson/index.html","http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pearson_symbol&oldid=558643456","/wiki/Help:Categories","/wiki/Category:Crystallography","/wiki/Category:Articles_with_German_language_external_links","/w/index.php?title=Special:UserLogin&returnto=Pe